  "answer": "**This specific passage and experiment—discrediting a philosopher-jurist's climate theory via an observation on half a sheep's tongue (with heating, freezing, fiber inspection under magnification), and concluding with a remark on a moral and political system resting on a scarcely solid base—are not present in the corpus.**\n\nMultiple searches were conducted for distinctive phrases and concepts from the query (e.g., \"sheep's tongue\", \"half tongue\", \"moral and political system\", \"scarcely solid base\", \"solid base\", \"tongue\" with \"experiment\"/\"heated\"/\"freezing\"/\"fibers\"/\"magnifying glass\", \"climate\" + \"tongue\"/\"sheep\"/\"Montesquieu\", and broader terms like \"experiment\", \"tongue\", \"sheep\") across English translations. All returned zero or irrelevant results (e.g., poetry or unrelated mentions). \n\nWiki cards and full chapters were examined for works critiquing climate theories (e.g., Charles Dunoyer's *Nouveau traité d'économie: VOL I*, ch. 2–3, where he engages Charles Comte and Montesquieu on race vs. climate; Charles Comte's *Traité de Législation: VOL III*, ch. 42+ on local circumstances and species superiority). While these discuss climate's influence (citing Montesquieu, Cabanis, etc.) and physiological works (e.g., Magendie), no sheep-tongue experiment appears, nor does the quoted conclusion. The corpus (37 works) covers relevant authors/topics like Comte/Dunoyer on Montesquieu's climate ideas but lacks this content.",
